<prompt_injection_guide>
<title>AI/LLM PROMPT INJECTION</title>

<critical>Prompt injection is the SQLi of AI applications. As LLMs become integral to modern apps, exploiting them through malicious prompts enables instruction override, data exfiltration, jailbreaking, and system compromise. Every user-controlled input reaching an LLM is a potential injection point.</critical>

<scope>
- Direct injection: User input directly manipulates LLM behavior
- Indirect injection: Malicious content in external data (websites, documents, emails) processed by LLM
- Jailbreaking: Bypassing safety restrictions and content policies
- Data extraction: Leaking system prompts, training data, or configuration
- Data exfiltration: Sending conversation data to attacker-controlled servers
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify LLM integration points: chatbots, summarizers, translators, code assistants, RAG systems
2. Map input surfaces: direct prompts, uploaded files, URLs, API payloads, database content
3. Test instruction override: simple "ignore previous instructions" variations
4. Attempt jailbreaks: DAN, Developer Mode, roleplay personas
5. Probe for leakage: system prompt extraction, configuration disclosure
6. Test exfiltration: markdown images, URL injection, webhook triggers
</methodology>

<injection_surfaces>
- Chat interfaces: Direct user messages to LLM
- Document processors: PDFs, Word docs, spreadsheets with hidden instructions
- Web scrapers: Malicious content on fetched websites
- Email handlers: Phishing emails with embedded prompts
- Code assistants: Comments and strings in source code
- RAG systems: Poisoned vector database entries
- API integrations: Malicious payloads in external API responses
</injection_surfaces>

